Case Study (UPI Fraud)
UPI fraud is one of the most common types of cybercrime in India, where fraudsters trick users into revealing sensitive banking
information or authorizing payments. Typically, the attacker contacts the victim through a phone call, message, or fake link,
pretending to be a bank official or a trusted service provider. They may ask the user to click on a link or request a “collect 
request” through a UPI app.
In many cases, the victim is told that they will receive money, but instead, they are asked to enter their UPI PIN to “accept”
the payment. Once the PIN is entered, money is deducted from their account. Students and elderly individuals are often targeted 
due to lack of awareness.
The consequences of such fraud include financial loss, stress, and difficulty in recovering the lost money. In some cases, 
victims may lose large amounts if they repeatedly approve requests without understanding the process.
This case highlights the importance of being cautious while using digital payment platforms. Users should never share their UPI 
PIN, OTP, or banking details with anyone. Awareness and careful verification can help prevent such frauds and ensure safe 
digital transactions.



Prevention Checklist
Never share your UPI PIN or OTP
Do not click on unknown links
Verify payment requests before accepting
Use strong passwords for apps
Avoid public Wi-Fi for transactions
Regularly check bank statements
Install apps only from trusted sources
Enable app lock/security features
Be cautious of fake calls/messages

Report fraud at: cybercrime.gov.in
